    body: "<p style='color:#6a4b8f;font-style:italic;margin-bottom:18px'>By Khyati Srivastava</p><p>Theo had lived his whole life aboard the Wanderer, a giant ship crawling between stars on a journey that would take three hundred years. He would never see the new world. His great-great-grandchildren might.</p><p>To pass the time, Theo wrote a message, attached it to a tiny signal beacon, and fired it into space. Hello, he wrote. I am Theo. I like puzzles and apples. Is anyone out there?</p><p>He did it as a joke. The nearest ship was unthinkably far away.</p><p>Eight months later, the comm panel chimed. A message had arrived, faint and slow. Hello, Theo, it read. I am Mara. I also like puzzles, but I have never tasted an apple. I live on the Aurora, three light-months behind you.</p><p>There was another ship. A second slow ark, following the same hopeful road, full of people just like him.</p><p>Theo and Mara became friends across the dark, sending one message every few months, trading riddles and stories. He described the taste of apples. She described the songs her ship sang at sleep-time.</p><p>Years passed. The two ships could never meet; their courses ran side by side but never crossed. Yet Theo no longer felt that the journey was empty.</p><p>When Theo grew old, he taught the children to send their own beacons into the night. Always answer a hello, he told them. Somewhere out there, someone is hoping you will.</p>",
