    category: "Sci-Fi",
    emoji: "🌱",
    excerpt: "A farmer plants a strange seed that arrives in a capsule from the future, with one urgent instruction.",
    created_at: "2026-05-26T06:00:00Z",
    body: "<p style='color:#6a4b8f;font-style:italic;margin-bottom:18px'>By Khyati Srivastava</p><p>Old Mr. Banerjee found the capsule in his field after a meteor shower. It was no meteor, though. It was a smooth metal pod, and inside lay a single silver seed and a note printed in his own handwriting.</p><p>Plant me, the note said. Trust yourself. From you, fifty years on.</p><p>Mr. Banerjee did not understand how his future self could send a seed back in time, but the handwriting was unmistakable, down to the crooked letter B. So he planted the silver seed and watered it every day.</p><p>It grew quickly into a tree with leaves like soft blue glass. Birds came from miles away to nest in it. When the wind passed through its branches, it made a sound like distant music that calmed everyone who heard it.</p><p>People traveled to sit beneath the tree when they felt worried or sad. Children studied better in its shade. The village, once quarrelsome, grew kinder and quieter.</p><p>Years later, when Mr. Banerjee was very old, scientists discovered how to send small objects briefly into the past. They asked him whether he had any wish.</p><p>He smiled and asked for one silver seed from the tree, and a sheet of paper. With a steady, crooked hand, he wrote a note to a younger version of himself, sealed it in a pod, and sent it back through the meteor shower of long ago.</p><p>He had always wondered who planted the future. Now he knew. It had been him all along.</p>",
