    body: "<p style='color:#6a4b8f;font-style:italic;margin-bottom:18px'>By Khyati Srivastava</p><p>The morning of the school bake sale, Mrs. Olu opened the kitchen to find disaster: all thirty-six prize cupcakes were gone. The trays were empty, the door was locked, and the only witness was Toby, the class hamster, snoozing in his cage.</p><p>Detective Club president Maya took the case. She studied the scene like a true investigator.</p><p>The window was open a crack, too small for a person. A trail of crumbs led from the counter to the window, then stopped. On the windowsill she found tiny muddy prints, far too small for shoes.</p><p>Maya looked outside. A sturdy branch from the old oak tree reached almost to the window. Below it, the grass was scattered with paper cupcake wrappers, all licked clean.</p><p>She climbed onto a chair and peered into the leaves. There, in a hollow of the oak, sat a family of fat, happy squirrels surrounded by frosting smears. They had squeezed through the gap, carried off the cupcakes one by one, and feasted in the tree.</p><p>Case solved. The thieves were not students at all.</p><p>Mrs. Olu sighed, then laughed. The class quickly baked a new batch, this time storing them in a sealed metal box. As a peace offering, they left a small dish of nuts beneath the oak.</p><p>The bake sale was a great success, and Maya earned a gold detective badge. The real lesson, she announced proudly, is that a good detective never assumes the culprit walks on two feet.</p>",
