    body: "<p style='color:#6a4b8f;font-style:italic;margin-bottom:18px'>By Khyati Srivastava</p><p>When Ms. Patel announced science fair partners, Ria got Theo, the quiet boy who sat in the back and never said a word. Ria sighed inside. She had wanted to win, and a partner who never talked did not seem promising.</p><p>But the first afternoon they worked together, something shifted. Theo, it turned out, was not boring. He was bursting with ideas. He just needed someone to listen long enough for them to come out. He wanted to build a tiny greenhouse to grow plants with colored light.</p><p>They spent two weeks after school in the lab, measuring, planting, arguing happily about which color of light worked best. Ria learned that Theo drew comics in his notebook and laughed at his own jokes before he finished them. Theo learned that Ria hummed when she was concentrating and was secretly very kind.</p><p>Their plants grew tallest under blue light, which surprised them both. But what surprised Ria more was how much she looked forward to those quiet afternoons, just the two of them and a row of small green shoots.</p><p>They won second place at the fair. Theo, who never spoke in class, stood beside the project and explained it to the judges without a single stammer, because Ria was standing next to him.</p><p>Afterward, he handed her a folded comic he had drawn. It showed two scientists under a blue light, smiling. The caption read, best partner. Ria kept it pressed in her notebook all year.</p>",
