    slug: "the-lighthouse-pen-pal",
    category: "Romance",
    emoji: "🕯️",
    excerpt: "A bottle washed up on the beach with a letter inside, beginning a friendship across the bay that Lila never saw coming.",
    created_at: "2026-04-15T18:00:00Z",
    body: "<p style='color:#6a4b8f;font-style:italic;margin-bottom:18px'>By Khyati Srivastava</p><p>Lila found the bottle wedged between two rocks after a storm. Inside was a letter, written in neat handwriting. To whoever finds this, it said, I live in the lighthouse across the bay, and it gets lonely out here. Write back, if you like. Send it to the sea.</p><p>So she did. She tucked her reply into the bottle and threw it as far as she could into the waves. Three days later it came back, with a new letter inside.</p><p>His name was Finn, and his family kept the old lighthouse on the far point. He could not visit town often, but he could see the lights of it at night and wonder who lived there. Now he knew at least one person did, a girl named Lila who collected sea glass and was learning to paint the ocean.</p><p>All summer the bottle traveled back and forth across the bay, carried by the tides and a little bit of luck. They wrote about everything. She painted him a picture of his own lighthouse. He pressed a tiny shell into his letter and told her it was the prettiest one he had found.</p><p>On the last day of summer, Lila walked to the beach and found Finn standing there in person, holding the bottle and looking nervous and hopeful all at once.</p><p>I rowed across, he said. I wanted to meet the girl who answered.</p><p>Lila smiled, the whole bright bay behind him. I am so glad you wrote, she said. Then they walked along the shore, no bottle needed at all.</p>",
