    body: "<p style='color:#6a4b8f;font-style:italic;margin-bottom:18px'>By Khyati Srivastava</p><p>Mira had a tin full of buttons. Big ones, tiny ones, a wooden one shaped like a star. Her brother laughed and called it junk, but Mira loved the little click they made when she shook the tin.</p><p>One rainy Monday, her teacher Mr. Patel arrived looking sad. The top button of his favorite coat had popped off and rolled into a drain. It was the last gift from his late grandmother, he said quietly, and now the coat would never close right again.</p><p>Mira remembered a smooth brass button at the bottom of her tin, carved with a tiny leaf. It looked old and kind, just like a grandmother might choose. At lunch she pressed it into Mr. Patel's hand.</p><p>He turned it over and over. His eyes went shiny. The carving, he whispered, was the very same leaf his grandmother used to draw.</p><p>That afternoon the whole class learned to sew. Wobbly stitches, knotted thread, laughter everywhere. Mr. Patel wore his mended coat for the rest of the year.</p><p>Mira's brother never called her tin junk again. Instead he started saving buttons too, just in case someone, someday, needed exactly the right one.</p>",
