    emoji: "🏃",
    excerpt: "Aanya finishes dead last in the city race, and discovers that the finish line is not the only thing worth crossing.",
    created_at: "2026-04-10T12:00:00Z",
    body: "<p style='color:#6a4b8f;font-style:italic;margin-bottom:18px'>By Khyati Srivastava</p><p>Aanya had trained all summer for the city fun run. She imagined breaking the ribbon first, medal gleaming on her chest.</p><p>But on race day her old knee ached, and runner after runner pulled ahead. By the halfway mark she was last, gasping, far behind the pack.</p><p>Up ahead a younger boy had tripped and sat crying on the curb, his lace tangled, the crowd already gone. Aanya could have passed him. Instead she stopped, knelt, and tied his shoe.</p><p>Come on, she said, holding out her hand. Let us finish together.</p><p>They walked, then jogged, the boy laughing now, Aanya cheering him on. They crossed the line dead last, long after the medals were handed out.</p><p>But the boy's mother was waiting, eyes brimming. A photographer caught the moment, and the next day the picture was everywhere: two tired runners, hands raised, grinning under the empty finish banner.</p><p>The caption read, Last place, first heart.</p><p>Aanya never won that medal. Yet for years afterward, strangers would stop her and say, You are the one who waited. And every time, she felt she had won the only race that mattered.</p>",
