    body: "<p style='color:#6a4b8f;font-style:italic;margin-bottom:18px'>By Khyati Srivastava</p><p>A sunflower seed fell from a bird's beak and tumbled into a narrow crack in the city sidewalk. All around it stretched gray concrete, hot and hard.</p><p>This is no place to grow, whispered a passing breeze. There is barely any soil here. Give up.</p><p>But the seed did not know how to give up. It only knew how to reach. It sent one thin root deeper into the dark, searching, until it found a sip of rainwater trapped below.</p><p>Days passed. A pale green shoot pushed up through the crack. People stepped over it. A skateboard nearly clipped it. Still it climbed.</p><p>A girl named Lila noticed the brave little stem and began bringing it water in an old juice bottle each morning on her way to school.</p><p>By summer's end, a single golden sunflower towered over the dull sidewalk, taller than Lila herself, its face turned to the sun.</p><p>Neighbors stopped to admire it. Someone painted a small sign beside it: If it can grow here, so can you.</p><p>The seed had no idea it had become a message. It only knew it had reached for the light, one stubborn inch at a time, and that had been enough.</p>",
