    emoji: "⏰",
    excerpt: "An old clockmaker who fears his best work is behind him repairs one final clock for a hopeful child.",
    created_at: "2026-04-08T06:00:00Z",
    body: "<p style='color:#6a4b8f;font-style:italic;margin-bottom:18px'>By Khyati Srivastava</p><p>Mr. Oduya had mended clocks for fifty years, but lately his hands trembled and his shop sat empty. The world wanted glowing screens now, not ticking gears. I am out of time, he told himself, and nearly closed the shutters for good.</p><p>One grey afternoon a girl named Esi pushed open the door, cradling a broken cuckoo clock. It was her grandmother's, she said. It had stopped on the very day her grandmother passed, and no one else would even try to fix it.</p><p>Mr. Oduya hesitated. His hands were not what they once were. But the hope in the girl's eyes was hard to refuse.</p><p>For three nights he worked by lamplight, easing each tiny gear back into place, steadying his fingers through every shake. On the fourth morning he wound the spring.</p><p>The clock ticked. Then, on the hour, a small wooden bird burst out singing, bright and clear.</p><p>Esi gasped and hugged the clock to her chest. It sounds just like her, she whispered.</p><p>Word spread of the clock that came back to life. Soon customers returned, young ones now, curious about the old craft. Mr. Oduya kept his shop open after all, having learned that it is never too late to begin again.</p>",
