    body: "<p style='color:#6a4b8f;font-style:italic;margin-bottom:18px'>By Khyati Srivastava</p><p>Every night, a pale lantern glow drifted across the misty marsh behind Nila's village. The grownups warned the children to stay away. It is a restless spirit, they whispered. Do not follow the light.</p><p>But Nila was curious, not afraid. One foggy evening she wrapped up warm, took her own little lantern, and followed the mysterious glow into the reeds.</p><p>The light bobbed ahead, never letting her catch up, leading her along a winding path. Strange shapes loomed in the fog, but they were only old willow trees dripping with mist.</p><p>At last the glow stopped above a half-sunken rowboat. Inside lay an even older lantern, its candle long dead, and beside it a faded locket.</p><p>Nila picked up the locket. It held a tiny painting of a girl who looked a little like her, and the name Mara, lost in the marsh a hundred years ago.</p><p>A soft sigh passed through the reeds, almost grateful, and the drifting glow gently faded for the very last time.</p><p>Nila brought the locket to the village museum, where Mara's story was finally told. The marsh light never returned. Some said the spirit had only ever wanted someone brave enough to bring her home.</p>",
