    author: "Khyati Srivastava",
    slug: "the-bee-who-wouldnt-buzz",
    category: "Animals",
    emoji: "🐝",
    excerpt: "Every bee in the hive has a job and a buzz to match it — except Zumi, whose silence turns out to be the very thing the hive needs most.",
    created_at: "2026-10-19T16:00:00Z",
    body: "<p style='color:#6a4b8f;font-style:italic;margin-bottom:18px'>By Khyati Srivastava</p><p>In the Hollowbranch hive, every bee had a buzz that matched her job — a sharp, urgent hum for the guards, a low contented drone for the honey-makers, a bright fast whirr for the scouts. Zumi had no buzz at all. She flew in near silence, which the other bees found unsettling, then irritating, then finally something they simply stopped mentioning out loud.</p><p>Nobody wanted a silent scout. A scout was supposed to buzz back news of good flowers, loud enough for the whole hive to hear and follow. Zumi was reassigned to hive-cleaning, the quietest job there was, and she didn't complain, because bees rarely do.</p><p>Then came the day a hawk began circling the meadow, and every loud, buzzing scout who went looking for flowers came home shaking and empty-handed, having given their position away instantly. The hive was three days from starving when the elder bee finally remembered the silent one nobody used anymore.</p><p>Zumi flew out without a sound, found a field thick with clover the hawk never noticed, and led the honey-makers back along a path so quiet the hawk never once looked down. The hive survived the week on a silence they'd almost thrown away, and after that, nobody in Hollowbranch ever again assumed that the bee with nothing to say had nothing worth hearing.</p>",
