    title: "Two Left Shoes",
    author: "Khyati Srivastava",
    slug: "two-left-shoes",
    category: "Kids",
    emoji: "👟",
    excerpt: "Milo's new sneakers are both, somehow, left feet — and the shoe store insists that's exactly how they're supposed to be.",
    created_at: "2026-10-19T17:00:00Z",
    body: "<p style='color:#6a4b8f;font-style:italic;margin-bottom:18px'>By Khyati Srivastava</p><p>Milo unboxed his brand-new sneakers on the first day of second grade and discovered, with dawning horror, that both shoes were left feet. He marched them straight back to Ferraro's Shoes, certain of a simple mistake.</p><p>Old Mr. Ferraro examined them, unbothered. \"Nope,\" he said. \"That's the pair. Special edition. Only made a few of those.\"</p><p>\"But they don't <em>work</em>,\" Milo said. \"You can't walk in two left shoes!\"</p><p>\"Can't you?\" Mr. Ferraro raised an eyebrow and nodded toward the door. \"Try.\"</p><p>Milo, annoyed, put them on right there in the shop and took a few stiff, awkward steps. It was strange, but not impossible — a little wobble on the outside edge of his right foot, nothing more. \"See?\" said Mr. Ferraro. \"Uncomfortable isn't the same as impossible. People forget that.\"</p><p>Milo wore the mismatched sneakers to school anyway, since his mom refused to buy another pair on short notice, and braced for laughter. Instead, three kids asked where he'd gotten them, and by lunchtime he'd told the story of the two left shoes so many times it had turned, somehow, from an embarrassment into his favorite thing about the whole first week. He never did get a matching pair. He stopped wanting one.</p>",
