    slug: "the-last-word-in-the-argument",
    category: "Inspirational",
    emoji: "🤝",
    excerpt: "Two best friends haven't spoken in three weeks over an argument neither of them can quite remember starting — until a shared trophy forces the question.",
    created_at: "2026-10-19T18:00:00Z",
    body: "<p style='color:#6a4b8f;font-style:italic;margin-bottom:18px'>By Khyati Srivastava</p><p>Amara and Deja had been best friends since kindergarten and hadn't spoken in three weeks, ever since an argument at lunch that had started over something so small neither of them could fully reconstruct it anymore — a seat, maybe, or a joke taken the wrong way. What they remembered clearly was who said what next, and next, until neither wanted to be the one who spoke first.</p><p>Then the science fair results were posted, and their project — built together back when they were still speaking, a working model volcano neither had touched since — took first place. The trophy had both their names engraved on it, and only one trophy existed.</p><p>They stood on opposite sides of the hallway, staring at the sign-up sheet demanding a single name for the school archive. Amara finally crossed the hallway first, not because she'd won the argument in her head, but because the trophy said both their names and she'd rather share something true than keep something broken.</p><p>\"We both get it,\" she said. \"One week each, then we trade. Deal?\"</p><p>Deja looked at the trophy, then at Amara, and felt three weeks of silence suddenly seem like a very silly amount of time. \"Deal,\" she said. Neither of them ever did remember exactly how the argument started. They remembered, instead, exactly how it ended — with somebody willing to go first.</p>",
