    author: "Khyati Srivastava",
    slug: "ode-to-the-last-slice-of-pizza",
    category: "Poetry",
    emoji: "🍕",
    excerpt: "A short, funny ode to the one slice left in the box — and the ancient family etiquette nobody wants to be the first to break.",
    created_at: "2026-10-20T11:00:00Z",
    body: "<p style='color:#6a4b8f;font-style:italic;margin-bottom:18px'>By Khyati Srivastava</p><p>Oh final slice, alone in your grease-stained box,<br>you sit there gleaming while nobody talks.<br>Six eyes upon you, six hands held still,<br>each one too polite to make the kill.</p><p>\"I'm full,\" says Dad, with a wistful glance.<br>\"Go on,\" says Mom, in a subtle dance<br>of offering that no one's meant to take —<br>a ritual old as the crust you make.</p><p>My sister cracks first. Her fork descends.<br>The table gasps. Old rules, world ends.<br>She splits you three ways, fair and true —<br>turns out the bravest thing to do<br>was never to grab you first and win,<br>but to cut you fair and let peace begin.</p><p>So here's to you, slice, cold now, and small:<br>you taught our whole family more than we recall<br>from any lecture, any speech, any book —<br>sharing tastes better than the food we took.</p>",
