    author: "Khyati Srivastava",
    slug: "the-loudest-kid-in-the-library",
    category: "Comedy",
    emoji: "📚",
    excerpt: "Benji has been banned from the library twice for talking too loud — so when he finally gets his library card back, he has exactly one rule to follow.",
    created_at: "2026-10-21T14:00:00Z",
    body: "<p style='color:#6a4b8f;font-style:italic;margin-bottom:18px'>By Khyati Srivastava</p><p>Benji had been asked to leave the Millbrook library twice — once for narrating an entire pirate battle out loud while reading alone at a table, and once for a passionate, unsolicited debate with a stranger about whether dragons could realistically fly. The librarian, Ms. Okonkwo, finally agreed to give him a third chance under exactly one condition: whisper only, or out for good.</p><p>Benji took this as seriously as an eight-year-old could. He whispered his way through an entire fantasy series, whispered his questions at the front desk, whispered so intensely at one point that Ms. Okonkwo had to lean in close just to hear him ask where the dragon books were shelved.</p><p>The real test came the day he found a book so good, so genuinely thrilling, that halfway through the final chapter he leapt out of his beanbag chair and nearly shouted before catching himself — freezing mid-motion, both hands clapped over his own mouth, eyes wide with the effort of containing it. He sat back down, took a breath, and whispered, fiercely, to absolutely no one: \"The dragon lived. The DRAGON LIVED.\"</p><p>Ms. Okonkwo, watching from the desk, decided that counted as following the rule in spirit if not quite in volume, and let it go. Benji never got banned again. He did, however, become locally famous for the most intense whispering anyone had ever witnessed.</p>",
