    title: "Signal Lost",
    author: "Khyati Srivastava",
    slug: "signal-lost",
    category: "Horror",
    emoji: "📻",
    excerpt: "The night-shift lighthouse keeper's radio picks up a distress call from a ship that sank forty years ago, repeating the exact same message, word for word.",
    created_at: "2026-10-21T17:00:00Z",
    body: "<p style='color:#6a4b8f;font-style:italic;margin-bottom:18px'>By Khyati Srivastava</p><p>Aldous had worked the night shift at Kestrel Point Lighthouse for eleven years and thought he'd heard every strange thing the old radio equipment could produce — static storms, ghost frequencies bleeding in from ships a hundred miles off, the ordinary electronic noise of a coastline at 3 a.m. What came through on a calm, clear November night was none of those things.</p><p>\"Mayday, mayday, this is the Corrigan, taking on water, position unknown, mayday—\" then silence, then, exactly ninety seconds later, the identical message again, word for word, same trembling voice, same pause in the same place.</p><p>Aldous checked the maritime records the next morning at the harbor office and found the Corrigan had gone down in a storm forty-one years earlier, three miles offshore, all hands lost, radio contact cut off mid-transmission at 3:14 a.m. — the exact time, to the minute, that he'd heard it repeat.</p><p>He mentioned it to old Captain Reyes, who ran the harbor tours, expecting disbelief. Instead, Reyes went quiet. \"My father was on the rescue boat that night,\" he said. \"They never found the crew. Just an empty life raft.\" Aldous kept the radio on every night after that, not out of fear anymore, but out of something closer to respect — a small, steady witness, forty years running, to a message that never got to finish, and a crew that never got to be found.</p>",
