    body: "<p style='color:#6a4b8f;font-style:italic;margin-bottom:18px'>By Khyati Srivastava</p><p>Aunt Coraline's recipe tin looked ordinary enough — dented, rust-spotted, held shut with a rubber band gone brittle with age. Delphine inherited it along with the rest of the kitchen, and spent her first week home emptying it card by card, sorting them into neat piles by category.</p><p>She emptied it completely on a Tuesday. On Wednesday, out of habit, she opened it again and found four new cards she hadn't seen before, in her aunt's unmistakable looping handwriting, for dishes Delphine had never once eaten in that kitchen.</p><p>She tested the tin properly after that — counted the cards, emptied it, counted again the next morning. It was never the same number twice, and never fewer than the day before. A note eventually surfaced among the newest batch, tucked at the bottom in handwriting slightly shakier than the rest: <em>I always meant to write down more than I had time for. Seems I finally have all the time in the world. Cook these for people you love, and don't ask questions you don't actually want answered.</em></p><p>Delphine stopped counting after that. She just cooked, one new card a week, filling her small apartment with dishes her aunt had apparently been dreaming up long after there was any kitchen left to make them in — a recipe box with no bottom, and, it turned out, no real end to the love it kept quietly serving up.</p>",
