    body: "<p style='color:#6a4b8f;font-style:italic;margin-bottom:18px'>By Khyati Srivastava</p><p>Marcus had rehearsed his answers in the mirror four times before walking into Halden's Hardware for his first-ever job interview, sweating through a shirt his mother had ironed twice. The owner, a broad, silent man named Halden, looked up from the register and studied him for a long moment before saying, \"You're the kid from the bus stop.\"</p><p>Marcus didn't remember at first. Then it came back — six months earlier, a man collapsed at the bus stop near school, and Marcus, fourteen and terrified, had been the only one who stopped, called for help, and stayed with him until the ambulance arrived, missing his own bus and getting home an hour late with no real explanation for his mother beyond \"someone needed help.\"</p><p>\"That was my heart,\" Halden said, tapping his own chest. \"Doctors said another five minutes and it would've been a different story. I never got your name. Asked around for weeks.\"</p><p>Marcus, mortified and unsure what to say, just shrugged. \"You needed help. That's all it was.\"</p><p>\"That's not all it was,\" Halden said, and slid the job application back across the counter, already signed. \"You start Monday. And Marcus — some interviews, the answer was decided a long time before you walked in the door.\"</p>",
