    title: "The Sock Puppet Diplomacy Incident",
    author: "Khyati Srivastava",
    slug: "the-sock-puppet-diplomacy-incident",
    category: "Comedy",
    emoji: "🧦",
    excerpt: "Two feuding kindergarten classes are forced to share a reading corner, and peace only arrives once the sock puppets start negotiating on their own terms.",
    created_at: "2026-10-22T12:00:00Z",
    body: "<p style='color:#6a4b8f;font-style:italic;margin-bottom:18px'>By Khyati Srivastava</p><p>Room 4 and Room 5 had been feuding, in the deeply serious way only kindergartners can feud, ever since a scheduling mix-up forced them to share the reading corner every Tuesday afternoon. Room 4 claimed the beanbags first by tradition. Room 5 disputed the tradition entirely. Neither side would budge.</p><p>Ms. Petrova, exhausted from refereeing daily, finally handed both classes a basket of mismatched socks and told them to \"work it out\" using puppets, mostly to buy herself five quiet minutes to drink her coffee while it was still warm.</p><p>What happened next surprised everyone. A striped sock representing Room 4 and a polka-dot sock representing Room 5 began, with great five-year-old solemnity, a formal negotiation: beanbags on even Tuesdays for Room 4, odd Tuesdays for Room 5, with a rotating \"Puppet Council\" to settle future disputes. The kids acted it out with more patience and fairness than the actual feud had shown in three straight weeks.</p><p>Ms. Petrova, watching from her cooling coffee, realized the puppets had simply given both sides permission to compromise without anyone losing face directly — nobody backing down, exactly, just two socks working it out on their behalf. The treaty held for the rest of the year. The Puppet Council, somewhat alarmingly, was later invoked to settle a dispute over crayon colors too.</p>",
