    title: "Static Electricity",
    author: "Khyati Srivastava",
    slug: "static-electricity",
    category: "Romance",
    emoji: "⚡",
    excerpt: "Two lab partners who can't stand each other discover the only thing they agree on is how badly their science project is going — and that turns out to be enough.",
    created_at: "2026-10-22T15:00:00Z",
    body: "<p style='color:#6a4b8f;font-style:italic;margin-bottom:18px'>By Khyati Srivastava</p><p>Farah and Callum had been paired for the science fair against both their wills, assigned alphabetically with zero regard for the fact that they'd disagreed about literally everything since the third grade — pineapple on pizza, the best Marvel movie, whether gym class should be mandatory.</p><p>Their project, a hand-cranked generator meant to demonstrate static electricity, was going badly. Spectacularly badly. Three failed prototypes, one minor singed eyebrow, and a growing pile of blame neither wanted to claim.</p><p>\"This is your fault,\" Farah said, for the fourth time that week, not remotely meaning it anymore.</p><p>\"Everything's my fault according to you,\" Callum shot back, also not really meaning it, and something about the familiar rhythm of the argument made them both, unexpectedly, laugh.</p><p>They rebuilt the fourth prototype together at midnight before the deadline, bickering the entire time about wire gauge and crank speed, and it finally worked — sparking cleanly, exactly on cue, in front of the judges the next morning. They placed third. Neither of them cared much about the ribbon. What surprised them both, walking home afterward, still arguing lightly about whether the third prototype could've worked with different wire, was that neither of them wanted the argument to actually end.</p>",
