    slug: "the-apprentice-ghostwriter",
    category: "Fantasy",
    emoji: "✍️",
    excerpt: "The town's actual ghost has been writing anonymous letters to lonely people for a hundred years — and he finally needs a living apprentice to keep the tradition going.",
    created_at: "2026-10-23T12:00:00Z",
    body: "<p style='color:#6a4b8f;font-style:italic;margin-bottom:18px'>By Khyati Srivastava</p><p>Elowen Marsh had haunted the same drafty study for a hundred and six years, and in all that time had found exactly one use for eternity: writing anonymous, encouraging letters to whichever townsperson seemed loneliest that season, slipping them under doors in handwriting nobody could trace.</p><p>He'd never needed help before. Ghosts don't tire. But his handwriting, he'd noticed with something like alarm, had begun to fade along with his memory of certain words, certain names — the slow, ordinary erosion that apparently came even for spirits who stayed too long. He needed someone living to carry it on, and settled, after much deliberation, on Odille, the withdrawn new girl at school who reminded him painfully of himself at that age.</p><p>He appeared to her only once, briefly, more suggestion than solid form, and explained the job simply: notice who's struggling, write to them kindly, never sign your name, never expect thanks. Odille, more curious than frightened, agreed.</p><p>She wrote her first letter that week, to a boy eating lunch alone every day, and slipped it into his locker before she could second-guess herself. He looked less alone at lunch the very next day. Elowen, watching from the drafty study, felt something in him finally settle after a hundred and six years — not because the job was done, but because it would keep being done, by someone with a beating heart and steadier handwriting than his.</p>",
