    body: "<p style='color:#6a4b8f;font-style:italic;margin-bottom:18px'>By Khyati Srivastava</p><p>The debate coach assigned topics randomly, which was how Priyanka and Owen — best friends, and in complete agreement that recess should be longer — found themselves assigned to argue opposite sides of exactly that question in front of the whole regional tournament.</p><p>Both of them believed, sincerely, that recess absolutely should be longer. Neither was willing to lose a debate, even one they'd been forced into arguing the wrong side of. What followed was, by all accounts, the strangest debate in tournament history: two competitors arguing with genuine, blistering passion against positions they privately held, each determined to win despite agreeing entirely with their opponent.</p><p>Owen, arguing against longer recess, found himself inventing increasingly elaborate reasoning about academic rigor he didn't believe a word of. Priyanka, arguing for it, barely had to try, which somehow made her furious that Owen was doing so disturbingly well arguing against something they both wanted.</p><p>The judges, baffled but impressed, called it a draw — the first tie in the tournament's twelve-year history. Afterward, Owen admitted he'd spent the whole debate desperately hoping he'd lose so the topic he actually believed in would officially win. \"That's the dumbest strategy I've ever heard,\" Priyanka said, laughing so hard she had to sit down. \"It's also,\" Owen said, \"apparently how you win an argument against your own opinion. Badly, and reluctantly.\"</p>",
