    body: "<p style='color:#6a4b8f;font-style:italic;margin-bottom:18px'>By Khyati Srivastava</p><p>Old Bertrand had performed with the same dummy, Whistler, for thirty-one years, and had long since stopped being unnerved by the faint sense — every performer gets it eventually — that Whistler seemed a little too alive between shows, settling into poses Bertrand didn't quite remember leaving him in.</p><p>He never asked questions. Whistler had made him a good living, and good livings were worth not looking too closely at. That was the arrangement, unspoken, for thirty-one years — until the night Bertrand collapsed alone in his dressing room, chest tight, phone just out of reach on the counter, and no one scheduled to check on him until morning.</p><p>He didn't remember exactly what happened next, only fragments: a small wooden weight dragging itself, joint by creaking joint, across the counter. A wooden hand, disproportionately strong, knocking the phone onto the floor beside him where his own fingers could finally reach it. By the time paramedics arrived, Whistler sat exactly where he always sat, slumped and lifeless on his stand, paint chipped, utterly ordinary.</p><p>Bertrand never told the doctors what he thought he remembered. He did, however, retire Whistler from every show after that, keeping him instead on a shelf in his own living room, dusted weekly, spoken to nightly, thanked — quietly, sincerely — for thirty-one years of an arrangement Bertrand finally understood had never really been one-sided at all.</p>",
