    body: "<p style='color:#6a4b8f;font-style:italic;margin-bottom:18px'>By Khyati Srivastava</p><p>The museum had no address, no listing, no entrance that stayed in the same place twice — Sable only found it because she'd taken a wrong turn home from school and, on a whim, followed an alley she'd never noticed before to a plain door marked simply \"THE MUSEUM OF ALMOST.\"</p><p>Inside were exhibits unlike any museum she'd visited: a wedding dress never worn, labeled with a date and two names who'd almost married and, for reasons the placard didn't explain, hadn't. A house key to a home never bought. A letter, never sent, from a man to the brother he'd almost reconciled with before it was too late.</p><p>Near the back, in a small glass case easy to miss, Sable found an exhibit with her own name on the placard: a single soccer trophy, dated for a tournament three years past, labeled \"Nearly won — quit the team two weeks before finals.\" She remembered that season clearly. She'd been scared of losing in front of everyone and had quit instead, telling herself it didn't matter.</p><p>The old curator found her staring at it, unable to look away. \"The museum doesn't judge the almosts,\" he said gently. \"It just remembers them, so you don't have to carry every one alone.\" Sable left without asking how to find the museum again. She had a feeling, somehow, that it would find her instead — right around the next moment she almost let something slip away.</p>",
