    body: "<p style='color:#6a4b8f;font-style:italic;margin-bottom:18px'>By Khyati Srivastava</p><p>Grumble the storm cloud had rained on every single picnic, parade, and outdoor birthday party in Meadowbrook for as long as anyone could remember, and the town had simply learned to schedule everything indoors, just in case. Nobody had ever asked him why he was so grumpy. They'd just accepted it, the way you accept a pothole in a road you drive every day.</p><p>The new young mayor did something nobody expected: she climbed the tallest hill with a paper umbrella and shouted up at him, not angrily, but kindly. \"You seem tired,\" she called. \"When's the last time you took a day off?\"</p><p>Grumble, who had never once been asked that question in three hundred years of drifting and drizzling, didn't have an answer. He'd simply always rained, because that was what clouds did, because nobody had ever suggested he might do anything else.</p><p>The mayor arranged it properly — an actual cloud vacation, a week drifting lazily over the quiet, uninhabited mountains where his rain could fall on nothing but rock and pine, no picnics to ruin, no parades to dampen. He came back a paler, fluffier, considerably less grumbly shade of gray. Meadowbrook still gets rained on sometimes. But now Grumble takes a vacation every summer, and the town has learned that even the crankiest things in life are sometimes just exhausted, not mean.</p>",
