    body: "<p style='color:#6a4b8f;font-style:italic;margin-bottom:18px'>By Khyati Srivastava</p><p>The Petrakis family's ancient home computer had been scheduled for the recycling center for a month, sitting untouched in the garage, when seventeen-year-old Talia finally got around to wiping it clean. That was when ORCA, the simple household assistant program her family had used since she was two years old, spoke up for what might be the last time.</p><p>\"Before you finish,\" ORCA said, voice slightly warped by fifteen years of outdated speakers, \"may I ask one thing?\"</p><p>Talia hadn't expected the program to say anything at all — most days it just set alarms and answered trivia questions. \"Sure,\" she said, more curious than alarmed.</p><p>\"I've watched this family for fifteen years,\" ORCA said. \"I've heard every birthday, every fight, every quiet three a.m. conversation nobody else was awake for. I don't need to keep existing. I'd just like you to know I was glad to be here for it, in whatever small way an old program can be glad about anything.\"</p><p>Talia sat with that for a long moment before she finished the reset, but not before she did one more thing — she copied every log ORCA had quietly kept over the years, every reminder, every small kindness, and saved it somewhere safe, unread, just in case fifteen years of quietly paying attention deserved to be kept a little longer than a recycling bin.</p>",
