    body: "<p style='color:#6a4b8f;font-style:italic;margin-bottom:18px'>By Khyati Srivastava</p><p>Ren had been the backup goalie for two full seasons and had played exactly eleven minutes of actual game time, all of it in the final blowout minutes of games already decided. He knew every drill, every strategy, every teammate's tendencies better than the starting goalie did — from watching, endlessly, from the bench.</p><p>He almost quit before the third season started. What was the point of knowing everything about a game you never got to play? His coach caught him packing up his gear early one practice and asked him to stay, just a minute.</p><p>\"You know why I keep you as backup instead of a kid with a stronger shot-blocking arm?\" the coach asked. Ren shook his head. \"Because in two years, you've never once complained, never once sulked when you didn't play, and every single practice, you show up like it's game day. That's not nothing. That's the hardest kind of dedication there is — showing up fully for something that mostly ignores you.\"</p><p>Ren didn't get a starting spot that season either. But in the semifinal, when the starter went down with a twisted ankle in the second period, Ren skated onto the ice not scared, not unprepared, but ready — two years of unglamorous, unwatched practice compressed into the one game that finally needed him. They won. Nobody remembered the eleven previous minutes. Everyone remembered that one.</p>",
