    body: "<p style='color:#6a4b8f;font-style:italic;margin-bottom:18px'>By Khyati Srivastava</p><p>In the village of Willowmere, every wind that blew through had a name, passed down through generations of weather-watchers: Old Bramble, the slow autumn wind that smelled of woodsmoke; Skittle, the mischievous spring gust that stole hats; Hollow, the low winter moan that rattled shutters and made everyone check the locks twice.</p><p>The new wind that arrived that autumn had no name, and refused every one Perry offered it — Whistler, Dusty, Barrel, nothing stuck, the wind simply shifting direction each time like a shrug. Perry, eleven and stubborn, decided to actually listen to it instead of naming it, the way you'd get to know a person before deciding what to call them.</p><p>She noticed, over weeks, that this wind never blew hard or mean. It arrived gently around people who were crying, stirring leaves just enough to be a small distraction, a small comfort, then moved quietly on. It circled playgrounds where lonely kids sat alone, nudging balls toward them as if inviting a game.</p><p>\"I think I finally understand you,\" Perry told it one evening, sitting on her porch as it curled softly around her shoulders like a shawl. \"You're not here to be noticed. You're here to help, quietly, and move on before anyone thinks to say thank you.\" The wind didn't answer, the way winds don't, but it settled around her a moment longer than usual before drifting off — and Perry decided some things are better left unnamed, so they stay exactly as free as they need to be.</p>",
