    category: "Horror",
    emoji: "🚢",
    excerpt: "The retired cruise ship has been empty for a decade, docked and rusting — but the intercom system still occasionally crackles to life with an announcement for a passenger who never boarded.",
    created_at: "2026-10-24T15:00:00Z",
    body: "<p style='color:#6a4b8f;font-style:italic;margin-bottom:18px'>By Khyati Srivastava</p><p>The SS Marisol had been decommissioned and docked at the edge of the harbor for eleven years, awaiting a scrapping that kept getting postponed, rusting quietly while gulls nested in her empty lifeboats. Security guard Damon walked her decks twice nightly, mostly out of boredom, and had long since stopped flinching at the creaks and groans of settling metal.</p><p>The intercom hadn't worked in a decade — cut power, corroded wiring, nothing that should have carried sound. So the first night it crackled on, mid-round, Damon nearly dropped his flashlight. \"Paging passenger Elena Vasquez,\" the ship's old automated voice announced, calm and cheerful as it must have sounded to a thousand real passengers over the decades. \"Elena Vasquez, please report to Guest Services on Deck Nine.\"</p><p>Damon checked the old passenger manifests out of morbid curiosity the next morning and found the name in the ship's final voyage records — Elena Vasquez, booked for the Marisol's very last cruise, marked in the margin: <em>cancelled, family emergency, refunded.</em> She had never actually boarded.</p><p>The announcement repeated every few weeks after that, always for Elena, always the same polite request. Damon eventually tracked down a phone number through old records and, feeling foolish, called it. An elderly woman answered, startled to hear the ship's name after so many years. \"I always regretted missing that trip,\" she admitted quietly. Damon didn't know what to say to that. He just said the ship still seemed to be waiting for her, and somehow, that seemed to be exactly the right thing to say.</p>",
