    body: "<p style='color:#6a4b8f;font-style:italic;margin-bottom:18px'>By Khyati Srivastava</p><p>Coral first found the bookmark tucked inside a library copy of an old adventure novel — a simple strip of pressed wildflowers laminated between cardstock, with a tiny handwritten note on the back: <em>Left here for whoever needed a good story today. Pass it on when you're done. —A friend</em>.</p><p>She meant to keep it. Instead, on impulse, she slid it into a different book before returning both, adding her own tiny line beneath the first: <em>Still true. Passing it forward.</em> She thought that would be the end of it.</p><p>Six months later, a friend from a library two towns over texted her a photo of the exact same bookmark, now covered in a dozen different handwritings, notes stacked in tiny cramped script down both sides — kids and adults alike, all strangers to each other, all adding a line before letting it travel on to whatever book, whatever reader, needed it next.</p><p>Coral never did find out who'd started it, and stopped trying, eventually deciding the mystery was better left unsolved. She checked in on its journey occasionally, tracking sightings other readers posted online — a bookmark that had, by the time she last heard of it, crossed eleven library systems and made it into the hands of at least two hundred strangers, all connected by nothing more than a pressed flower and the shared, quiet agreement to pass a good thing along.</p>",
