    body: "<p style='color:#6a4b8f;font-style:italic;margin-bottom:18px'>By Khyati Srivastava</p><p>Cole had carried the ball for every meaningful yard the Ashgrove Hawks had gained all season, and everyone, including Cole, expected him to carry it for the last one too — one yard from the championship, twelve seconds on the clock, the whole town on its feet.</p><p>He went down hard on the play before, ankle twisted wrong beneath a defender, and the sideline went dead silent watching him carried off, season and championship suddenly balanced on whoever came in next. That was Benji, second-string, who'd touched the ball maybe a dozen times all year and never once in a moment that mattered this much.</p><p>\"You've got this,\" Cole said from the stretcher, gripping Benji's jersey for one second before they carried him further away. \"You've watched every one of my runs from the sideline all year. You know exactly what to do.\"</p><p>Benji didn't feel ready. He lined up anyway, ball in his hands, twelve seconds, one yard, an entire town's held breath riding on legs that had spent all season believing they were only good enough to watch. He put his head down and ran the way he'd imagined it a hundred times from the bench, and crossed the line with half a second left on the clock.</p><p>Cole hugged him first, ankle and all, hobbling on crutches someone had found for him. \"Told you,\" he said. Benji didn't have words for it yet. He just held onto the ball, the actual ball, from the actual game, and let himself believe, finally, that watching from the bench all year hadn't been nothing after all.</p>",
