    excerpt: "A short poem about the first snowfall of the year, and everything it quietly brings back with it.",
    created_at: "2026-10-24T18:00:00Z",
    body: "<p style='color:#6a4b8f;font-style:italic;margin-bottom:18px'>By Khyati Srivastava</p><p>The first snow falls the way it always does —<br>quiet, uncertain, testing the ground,<br>and something in my chest goes soft and slow<br>the way it does each year, without a sound.</p><p>It isn't just the cold that makes me still.<br>It's every winter folded into this one:<br>the mitten I once lost and never found,<br>my grandpa's boots stamped hard against the sun.</p><p>The snowman we built crooked, melting fast.<br>The hot cocoa that burned my tongue too soon.<br>A hundred small forgotten winter days<br>come drifting back beneath this white cocoon.</p><p>So let it fall. Let it cover up the yard,<br>the fence, the porch, the year that's nearly done.<br>Some things get lighter underneath the snow.<br>Some memories only surface once begun.</p><p>I'll step outside and leave my boot-prints there,<br>one more winter added to the rest —<br>proof that I was here, that I still care<br>to greet the cold and call this season blessed.</p>",
