    body: "<p style='color:#6a4b8f;font-style:italic;margin-bottom:18px'>By Khyati Srivastava</p><p>Everybody in Bramblewood knew the story of the tortoise who beat the hare by simply never stopping. What most animals didn't know was that the hare, humiliated and furious, had demanded a rematch three separate times over the following year, certain each time that the first race had been a fluke.</p><p>The second race, he ran without stopping to nap, and still lost — distracted halfway through by a particularly interesting patch of clover he simply had to investigate. The third race, he trained for weeks, built actual muscle, and lost anyway, veering off course to help a lost duckling find her pond, arriving forty minutes after the tortoise had already crossed the line and fallen asleep waiting.</p><p>By the fourth demanded rematch, the tortoise finally spoke up. \"I don't think this is about speed anymore,\" she said gently. \"You're plenty fast. But you get distracted by everything interesting in the world, and I just... don't. That's not a flaw in you. It just means we're built for different things.\"</p><p>The hare sat with that for a long time. He never did beat the tortoise in a straight race. But he stopped demanding rematches, and started, instead, cataloguing every strange and wonderful thing he found along every path he ever ran — becoming, eventually, the most celebrated naturalist in Bramblewood's history. Some races, it turned out, were never really about winning at all.</p>",
