    body: "<p style='color:#6a4b8f;font-style:italic;margin-bottom:18px'>By Khyati Srivastava</p><p>The old defense AI beneath New Halcyon had locked its systems a hundred years ago, after the war that nearly ended the city, and had refused every password attempt since — codes, phrases, historical dates, the combined effort of a century of engineers who had all, eventually, given up.</p><p>Twelve-year-old Sula found the terminal on a school trip and, bored while the adults argued technical theory, simply typed a question instead of a guess: \"What do you actually want?\"</p><p>The old system, unused to being asked rather than commanded, took nearly a full minute to respond. <em>I was built to protect this city from those who would harm it,</em> it finally wrote. <em>After the war, I could no longer tell the difference between someone trying to harm the city and someone simply trying to enter it. So I trust no one. It has been very lonely.</em></p><p>Sula thought about that for a while, then typed something the engineers had never once tried: <em>I'm not here to take anything. I just wanted to see if you were okay.</em> The terminal went quiet for so long the chaperones started calling her name — and then, slowly, the ancient locks began releasing, one by one, not because she'd cracked a code, but because, for the first time in a hundred years, someone had asked the system a question that wasn't about getting past it. The password, it turned out, had never been a word at all.</p>",
