    slug: "the-substitute-grandmother",
    category: "Drama",
    emoji: "👵",
    excerpt: "When Kavi's grandmother moves too far away to visit, the elderly woman next door offers to fill in — an arrangement neither of them expected to actually need.",
    created_at: "2026-10-25T12:00:00Z",
    body: "<p style='color:#6a4b8f;font-style:italic;margin-bottom:18px'>By Khyati Srivastava</p><p>Kavi's grandmother moved three states away to be closer to his aunt, and the goodbye at the airport had been the kind that leaves a person hollowed out for weeks afterward — video calls helped, but they weren't the same as the smell of her kitchen or the specific way she braided his sister's hair.</p><p>Mrs. Alcott next door noticed him sitting alone on his porch steps more often that autumn and, one afternoon, simply sat down beside him with two mugs of tea she hadn't asked if he wanted. \"I don't have any grandchildren of my own nearby either,\" she said. \"Seems like a waste, two lonely people living twenty feet apart.\"</p><p>It wasn't a replacement — Kavi was careful about that, careful with himself, careful to still call his real grandmother every Sunday. But Mrs. Alcott taught him to bake bread the way her own mother had, badly at first, then well, and listened to his day the specific patient way grandmothers seem to have a monopoly on, and somehow, without either of them ever officially naming the arrangement, became something real and separate and equally important.</p><p>He introduced the two of them over video call eventually, nervous about how it might feel. His actual grandmother teared up, delighted rather than jealous. \"Thank you for taking care of my boy,\" she told Mrs. Alcott, and Mrs. Alcott said, simply, \"He's taken care of me plenty too.\" Some families, Kavi learned that year, grow in directions nobody plans for, and turn out fine anyway.</p>",
