    body: "<p style='color:#6a4b8f;font-style:italic;margin-bottom:18px'>By Khyati Srivastava</p><p>By the time Otto reached the classroom dress-up box on Costume Day, the dragon suit was gone, the astronaut helmet was gone, even the mediocre pirate hat was gone, claimed by kids who'd sprinted from the bus the second the doors opened. What remained, crumpled at the very bottom, was a lumpy brown felt costume of indeterminate shape labeled, in faded marker, \"Potato.\"</p><p>Otto considered going costumeless. Then, with the specific stubbornness of an eight-year-old who refuses to be embarrassed by circumstance, he put it on completely — every lumpy inch — and walked into class with his chin up like he'd chosen it on purpose.</p><p>\"I'm not just a potato,\" he announced to the room, before anyone could laugh. \"I'm the most important vegetable in this school. You can't have fries without me. You can't have mashed potatoes on Thanksgiving without me. I am essential. I am beloved. I am carbohydrates.\"</p><p>The class, disarmed entirely by his commitment, ended up voting him Best Costume that year — not despite the potato suit, but because of exactly how thoroughly he'd refused to be embarrassed by it. Otto wore that potato costume with pride for the rest of the day, and told the story so many times afterward that by the following Halloween, three other kids specifically requested it, and the school had to buy a second one.</p>",
