    category: "Poetry",
    emoji: "✨",
    excerpt: "A short poem for the small, unnamed stars that never made it into any constellation — and the quiet dignity of shining anyway.",
    created_at: "2026-10-25T16:00:00Z",
    body: "<p style='color:#6a4b8f;font-style:italic;margin-bottom:18px'>By Khyati Srivastava</p><p>Not every star gets stitched into a shape,<br>a hunter's belt, a bear, a winking eye.<br>Some just burn quietly at the edges,<br>unnamed, unmapped, forgotten by the sky's<br>own storytellers, who drew lines between<br>the loud, bright ones and called the rest just space.</p><p>But stand out on a truly moonless night<br>and tilt your head — you'll find them anyway:<br>small steady lights with no myth to their name,<br>no hero's outline tracing out their place.<br>They shine the same. They burn the same amount.<br>They just weren't chosen for the story's frame.</p><p>I think of them on days I feel unseen,<br>uncast, unnamed, no constellation mine —<br>and remember light doesn't need a shape<br>to travel light-years just to softly shine.<br>Some stars get myths. Some just get to be.<br>Both, in the end, are equally divine.</p>",
