    title: "The Group Project Nobody Wanted",
    author: "Khyati Srivastava",
    slug: "the-group-project-nobody-wanted",
    category: "Comedy",
    emoji: "📋",
    excerpt: "Four kids who can't stand each other get assigned the same group project — and the only thing they agree on is how much they resent the assignment.",
    created_at: "2026-10-26T12:00:00Z",
    body: "<p style='color:#6a4b8f;font-style:italic;margin-bottom:18px'>By Khyati Srivastava</p><p>Ms. Guerrero assigned groups alphabetically, a decision that landed Beatrix, Cormac, Dahlia, and Elián — four kids with a well-documented history of not getting along — on the same volcano diorama project, due in two weeks, worth thirty percent of their grade.</p><p>The first meeting lasted four minutes before it dissolved into an argument about whose house to work at. The second meeting produced a volcano so lopsided it looked more like a collapsed hill. The third meeting, held in tense silence at the kitchen table of whoever's parents were least likely to intervene, finally produced something resembling progress, mostly because Dahlia, exhausted, simply started assigning tasks like a tiny, furious general and nobody had the energy left to argue.</p><p>Something strange happened around the ninth day: they discovered, almost by accident, that Cormac was weirdly good at the chemical reaction, Beatrix had genuine painting talent, Elián was surprisingly patient with the tedious papier-mâché layering, and Dahlia's bossiness, properly channeled, made an excellent project manager. Their volcano, when it finally erupted in front of the class, wasn't just functional — it was the best one in the room.</p><p>They didn't become best friends. They still argued about nearly everything unrelated to volcanoes. But four kids who'd started the project actively avoiding each other ended it high-fiving over a foaming baking-soda eruption, and Ms. Guerrero, watching from her desk, allowed herself a small, smug smile — she'd put them together on purpose.</p>",
