    title: "The Elevator Pitch",
    author: "Khyati Srivastava",
    slug: "the-elevator-pitch",
    category: "Inspirational",
    emoji: "🛗",
    excerpt: "A shy inventor gets exactly ninety seconds trapped in an elevator with the one investor who could change everything — and has to decide whether to say something.",
    created_at: "2026-10-26T15:00:00Z",
    body: "<p style='color:#6a4b8f;font-style:italic;margin-bottom:18px'>By Khyati Srivastava</p><p>Fifteen-year-old Nemo had spent six months building a working water filter out of scrap materials for the school science fair, cheap enough for villages without clean water access, and had rehearsed the pitch a hundred times in his bedroom mirror without ever once finding the nerve to say it to a real person.</p><p>The elevator at the regional science expo stopped between floors with a jolt, trapping him for ninety seconds — he counted later — with exactly one other person: a woman whose badge read, in small print he almost missed, CHIEF INVESTMENT OFFICER, GREENLIGHT VENTURES.</p><p>He had two choices. Stay silent, the way six months of rehearsal-only courage usually meant he would. Or say something, anything, in the ninety seconds the universe had apparently decided to hand him. \"I built a water filter that costs four dollars to make and removes ninety-nine percent of contaminants,\" he blurted, voice cracking on the word contaminants. \"I know this is weird. I just — I might not get another chance to tell someone who could actually do something with it.\"</p><p>The elevator doors opened before she could respond. She stepped out, then paused, and turned back. \"Booth number?\" she asked. He told her, hands shaking. She visited that afternoon, spent twenty minutes examining his prototype, and left her card. His invention didn't change the world overnight. But it got funded, eventually, because a terrified kid had decided ninety trapped seconds were worth more than staying comfortably, permanently quiet.</p>",
