    title: "The Doorbell That Rings Backwards",
    author: "Khyati Srivastava",
    slug: "the-doorbell-that-rings-backwards",
    category: "Horror",
    emoji: "🔔",
    excerpt: "The doorbell at 14 Hollow Lane rings a full thirty seconds before anyone actually presses it — giving the homeowners just enough warning, and just enough dread.",
    created_at: "2026-10-27T15:00:00Z",
    body: "<p style='color:#6a4b8f;font-style:italic;margin-bottom:18px'>By Khyati Srivastava</p><p>The Ferreira family noticed it within their first month at 14 Hollow Lane: the doorbell rang exactly thirty seconds before anyone actually stepped onto the porch to press it, every single time, with a consistency too precise to be a wiring fault, though three separate electricians insisted, baffled, that nothing was actually wrong with the circuit.</p><p>They adapted quickly, the way people adapt to almost anything given enough time — thirty seconds became a small, useful warning, enough time to mute the television or hide a mess before answering the door. It stopped being unsettling and started being merely strange, filed away with the other minor oddities every old house seems to accumulate.</p><p>Then came the night it rang with absolutely no one on the porch. Twelve-year-old Mateo checked twice, the porch empty both times, the street dark and undisturbed. Thirty seconds later, right on the doorbell's usual schedule, three sharp knocks landed on the door itself, from something that had apparently arrived exactly when the bell predicted, without ever walking up the visible path to get there.</p><p>The family never did figure out what, precisely, the bell was actually warning them about that night, or why it had never repeated the incident since. They kept the house — the warning, they eventually decided, was more useful than frightening, thirty seconds being exactly enough time to decide, calmly, whether answering the door was something they actually wanted to do.</p>",
