    slug: "the-case-of-the-backwards-birthday",
    category: "Mystery",
    emoji: "🎂",
    excerpt: "Every gift Priya receives on her twelfth birthday is something she'll only need years from now — a mystery her whole family swears they can't explain.",
    created_at: "2026-10-29T17:00:00Z",
    body: "<p style='color:#6a4b8f;font-style:italic;margin-bottom:18px'>By Khyati Srivastava</p><p>Priya's twelfth birthday started normally enough until the gifts turned strange: a car key fob with no car attached, a graduation cap two sizes too big, a set of house keys labeled \"first apartment\" in her aunt's handwriting. Her family swore, one after another, they'd simply grabbed the wrong wrapped boxes — an honest, forgettable mix-up.</p><p>Priya, suspicious by nature and recently obsessed with detective novels, didn't buy it. She interviewed each relative individually, notebook in hand, and found their stories didn't quite line up — everyone remembered wrapping something different than what had ended up in her hands.</p><p>The real answer came from her grandmother, cornered in the kitchen during cleanup, who finally admitted the truth with a guilty little laugh: she'd started a tradition, secretly, of buying Priya's future milestones early, one per year, storing them away and wrapping the wrong year's gift on purpose whenever she felt Priya needed a nudge to dream a little bigger about who she might become.</p><p>\"You were being so hard on yourself about a math test that week,\" her grandmother admitted. \"I wanted you to remember there's a whole future ahead of you, bigger than one bad grade.\" Priya kept every backwards gift after that, unwrapped a little early each year going forward, a strange and oddly comforting family tradition — proof, wrapped in ribbon, that someone in her life was always quietly betting on everything good still coming her way.</p>",
