    body: "<p style='color:#6a4b8f;font-style:italic;margin-bottom:18px'>By Khyati Srivastava</p><p>He doesn't chase the ball the way he used to.<br>His muzzle's greyer than it was last spring.<br>He takes the stairs more slowly, one at a time,<br>and sleeps through half of everything.</p><p>But he still knows the sound of my door creaking<br>the nights I come home sad and say nothing at all.<br>He still gets up, slow joints and all, to meet me,<br>gets up before I've even reached the hall.</p><p>He doesn't need the words I never say out loud.<br>He just leans warm against my leg and stays.<br>Fourteen years of loyalty, no explanation needed —<br>just showing up, the same, through all my days.</p><p>I know the years ahead of us are fewer<br>than the ones already spent curled at my feet.<br>So I sit with him a little longer these days.<br>Some love doesn't need words to be complete.</p>",
