    body: "<p style='color:#6a4b8f;font-style:italic;margin-bottom:18px'>By Khyati Srivastava</p><p>Fairy godmother Wilhelmina had granted wishes for four hundred years without a single hitch, but arrived at young Odessa's cottage on the night of the harvest ball to discover, with rising horror, that the second half of the transformation spell had simply slipped her mind entirely — pumpkin to carriage, she remembered fine. Carriage back to pumpkin at midnight, the crucial safety clause, was gone, vanished, nowhere in her four-centuries-old memory.</p><p>\"I don't suppose you have a spellbook,\" Odessa asked, watching the increasingly panicked godmother pat down pockets that didn't exist.</p><p>\"I never needed one before,\" Wilhelmina admitted, mortified. \"This has literally never happened. I'm four hundred and twelve years old.\"</p><p>They solved it together, in the end, the unglamorous practical way — Odessa simply agreed to leave the ball early, well before midnight, rather than trust an unreliable spell to reverse itself on schedule. The carriage ride home was lovely regardless, ball gown intact, no humiliating public transformation required.</p><p>Wilhelmina remembered the spell perfectly the very next morning, of course, the way forgotten things so often return exactly when you no longer need them. She apologized profusely, mortified for weeks afterward. Odessa waved it off entirely. \"Honestly,\" she said, \"leaving early on my own terms felt better than being forced out by a deadline anyway. Maybe your memory did me a favor.\" Wilhelmina liked that explanation considerably better than her own guilt, and used it, from then on, as her official excuse whenever anyone asked about the incident.</p>",
