    body: "<p style='color:#6a4b8f;font-style:italic;margin-bottom:18px'>By Khyati Srivastava</p><p>The Ashworth estate had hosted the town's biggest annual gala for over a century, and every single year, without fail, the final headcount at the door came up one guest higher than the confirmed invitation list — a discrepancy so consistent that longtime attendees simply stopped mentioning it, chalking it up to some clerical quirk nobody bothered investigating.</p><p>Priyanka, new to town and unaware of the tradition, actually tried to solve it her first year attending, carefully counting every face in every photograph taken that night, cross-referencing against the guest list twice. The numbers matched perfectly in every photo except one — a group shot on the main staircase, where a figure stood at the very back edge of the frame, formally dressed, entirely unfamiliar, matching no name on any list she could find.</p><p>She showed the photo to the estate's elderly caretaker, half-expecting an explanation about a photobombing stranger. The caretaker studied it for a long moment, unsurprised. \"That's just Mr. Ashworth,\" he said simply. \"The original owner. He built this house for parties exactly like this one, and never got to attend a single one — died the week before the first gala, over a century ago. He shows up anyway, every year. We stopped trying to uninvite him decades back.\"</p><p>Priyanka kept that photograph, uneasy but strangely moved by it, and found herself, the following year, quietly leaving one extra place setting at her own table — not out of fear, exactly, but out of a growing sense that a man who'd never gotten his party deserved, at the very least, to keep attending the one he'd built.</p>",
