    body: "<p style='color:#6a4b8f;font-style:italic;margin-bottom:18px'>By Khyati Srivastava</p><p>Some days the ground feels thin beneath my feet,<br>a lake half-frozen, cracking with each stride,<br>and every step forward is its own small risk —<br>no proof the surface holds on the other side.</p><p>I've learned to walk it anyway, slow and light,<br>testing each patch before I trust my weight,<br>not because the fear has ever fully left me,<br>but because standing still won't change my fate.</p><p>The cracks don't mean the ice is sure to break.<br>Sometimes they're just the sound of ice that's thick<br>enough to hold you, settling and shifting,<br>groaning through a growth that isn't quick.</p><p>So I keep walking, careful, listening close,<br>trusting my own weight more than I used to do.<br>Thin ice taught me something solid ground never could:<br>how brave it is to move when you're not sure it'll hold you through.</p>",
