    created_at: "2026-10-31T17:00:00Z",
    body: "<p style='color:#6a4b8f;font-style:italic;margin-bottom:18px'>By Khyati Srivastava</p><p>Flight attendant Marisol had worked the same cross-country route for six years and had heard the story from enough colleagues to half-believe it herself: on every single flight, regardless of who sat in seat 14C, the overhead reading light switched on by itself exactly one hour into the journey and stayed lit for exactly one hour more, whether or not the seat was occupied at all.</p><p>Maintenance had checked the wiring four separate times over the years and found nothing wrong, nothing that should have caused a malfunction so precise and so consistent. Marisol finally decided to actually investigate properly on a quiet red-eye flight with the seat empty, watching the clock as the hour mark approached.</p><p>The light clicked on exactly on schedule, and this time, curious rather than spooked, she sat down in 14C herself and simply waited to see what, if anything, might happen next. Nothing dramatic occurred — no ghostly visitor, no whispered message. Just a quiet hour of reading light over an empty seat, on a plane thirty thousand feet above a country full of ordinary sleeping passengers.</p><p>She finally found the answer buried in old maintenance logs: the aircraft had been part of a fleet retrofit fifteen years earlier, replacing a jet that had been permanently grounded after a technical fault — a fault first noticed by an engineer's daughter who'd insisted on reading during a long test flight in that exact seat, catching an issue that likely saved lives. Marisol never did figure out why the light still honored her one habitual hour of reading, fifteen years and several planes later. She just made sure, every flight after that, to let seat 14C have its hour undisturbed.</p>",
