    category: "Fantasy",
    emoji: "🌱",
    excerpt: "In old Yara's garden, every plant grows in reverse — flowers wilt into buds, fruit shrinks into blossoms — and the whole village depends on it more than they realize.",
    created_at: "2026-11-01T11:00:00Z",
    body: "<p style='color:#6a4b8f;font-style:italic;margin-bottom:18px'>By Khyati Srivastava</p><p>Every garden in the valley grew the ordinary way except old Yara's, tucked behind her cottage at the edge of Thistledown — a plot where flowers unfurled backward into tight buds by evening, where apples shrank slowly back into blossoms across a season, where the whole visible order of growing things seemed to run gently, deliberately, in reverse.</p><p>The villagers found it unsettling for a generation or two, giving the garden and its keeper a wide, superstitious berth. It was only during the terrible blight year, when every ordinary garden in the valley failed entirely, that anyone thought to ask Yara for help — and discovered, to their shared astonishment, that a garden growing backward through time could be coaxed, carefully, to grow forward again on demand, undoing months of failed harvest in a single reversed, accelerated bloom.</p><p>Yara fed half the valley that winter from a garden nobody had bothered understanding until they desperately needed it, and explained, patiently, to the children who finally asked the right questions: \"Most things that look wrong from the outside are just following rules nobody's bothered to learn yet. My garden isn't broken. It's just working differently than you expected — and different isn't the same thing as wrong.\"</p><p>The village kept a much closer eye on Yara's strange, backward garden after that winter, no longer out of suspicion but out of gratitude, and made sure, going forward, to ask questions about the things that confused them before deciding those things were dangerous.</p>",
