    body: "<p style='color:#6a4b8f;font-style:italic;margin-bottom:18px'>By Khyati Srivastava</p><p>Milo and Dee had planned their soccer ball retrieval mission with the seriousness of actual heist professionals — reconnaissance sketches, a timed distraction involving Dee's little brother and a very committed fake asthma attack, and, as the crowning centerpiece of the plan, a daring getaway in Milo's grandfather's golf cart, borrowed without permission and top speed of exactly six miles per hour.</p><p>The infiltration went, remarkably, according to plan. The ball was liberated from the bully Trent's backyard shed with genuine tactical precision. The getaway, however, immediately fell apart the moment Milo floored the golf cart's accelerator and the vehicle responded with the majestic urgency of a determined tortoise, humming along at a pace that Trent, on foot, easily kept pace with while shouting increasingly confused threats.</p><p>What followed was less a dramatic escape and more an extremely slow, extremely public procession down three blocks of suburban street, Trent jogging leisurely alongside the golf cart the entire way, until the absolute absurdity of the situation finally broke through everyone's seriousness at once, and all three kids ended up laughing too hard to maintain either the chase or the getaway.</p><p>Trent got his shed key back and a lecture from his own mom about hoarding other kids' soccer balls. Milo and Dee got the ball back and a story that outlived the actual soccer season by several years. The golf cart, retired from active heist duty after that, went back to its usual job of hauling grandpa's gardening tools, no worse for its brief and thoroughly unglamorous life of crime.</p>",
