    category: "Drama",
    emoji: "✉️",
    excerpt: "A father finds a box of unsent letters his son wrote during summer camp years ago — and reads, for the first time, everything his son was too afraid to actually say out loud.",
    created_at: "2026-11-01T13:00:00Z",
    body: "<p style='color:#6a4b8f;font-style:italic;margin-bottom:18px'>By Khyati Srivastava</p><p>Desmond found the shoebox while helping his now-grown son move apartments — a dozen envelopes, never mailed, addressed to himself in handwriting that was unmistakably twelve-year-old Theo's, from the summer camp he'd attended the year his parents separated.</p><p>Theo, embarrassed, tried to grab the box before his father could open it. Desmond, curious and gentle, asked if he could read just one. Theo, after a long pause, said okay.</p><p>The letter wasn't angry, the way Desmond had half-expected given how quiet and withdrawn Theo had been that whole difficult summer. It was simply honest, in the specific unguarded way only a homesick twelve-year-old writing to no one in particular can be: <em>I miss when you and Mom weren't fighting. I know I'm not supposed to say I miss it because everyone keeps telling me it's better now. But I still miss it. I didn't want to tell you that because I didn't want you to feel bad. So I'm not sending this. I just needed to write it somewhere.</em></p><p>Desmond sat with that letter for a long time, twenty years late, understanding for the first time exactly how much his twelve-year-old son had quietly carried alone that summer, protecting his parents from a grief he'd never let them see. He didn't apologize exactly — some things, this many years on, were beyond apology. He just hugged his son, now nearly thirty, and told him he was sorry he hadn't asked harder back then. Theo, surprised by his own tears, said it was okay. It had taken him twenty years to believe that himself, but he finally did.</p>",
