    excerpt: "A poem for every abandoned sketch, unfinished song, and half-written story sitting quietly in a drawer — and why they still matter.",
    created_at: "2026-11-01T16:00:00Z",
    body: "<p style='color:#6a4b8f;font-style:italic;margin-bottom:18px'>By Khyati Srivastava</p><p>There's a drawer of half-finished things in my room —<br>a sketch that never got its final line,<br>a song with just two verses, no real chorus,<br>a story that trails off mid-sentence, undefined.</p><p>I used to think unfinished meant a failure,<br>proof I'd started something I couldn't complete.<br>But lately I've been wondering if trying<br>still counts for something, even incomplete.</p><p>The sketch still taught my hand a little something.<br>The song still found two verses' worth of true.<br>The story, though it never found its ending,<br>still held a thought I hadn't said, brand new.</p><p>So maybe half-finished isn't wasted effort.<br>Maybe it's just practice, quietly stored —<br>proof I keep on reaching, keep on trying,<br>even when the whole thing's not yet toward.</p><p>I'll finish some. I'll leave some in the drawer.<br>Both kinds still mattered while I made them, all the same.</p>",
