    excerpt: "While everyone else rushes to build their science fair volcano from memory, one patient kid actually reads the whole instruction manual first — and it changes everything.",
    created_at: "2026-11-01T18:00:00Z",
    body: "<p style='color:#6a4b8f;font-style:italic;margin-bottom:18px'>By Khyati Srivastava</p><p>Every other kid in Ms. Okafor's class tore into their science fair volcano kits the moment they were handed out, eager to start mixing baking soda and vinegar without so much as glancing at the instruction booklet tucked at the bottom of the box. Priti, methodical by nature and mildly allergic to skipping steps, actually read the whole thing first, cover to cover, while her classmates' volcanoes began collapsing around her in various small chemical disasters.</p><p>She got teased a little for it — \"why are you reading a manual, just mix stuff together\" — but kept at her own careful pace, following each step in order: base layer first, structural support second, chemical reaction only after everything else had properly set and dried, exactly as the ignored instructions specified.</p><p>The other volcanoes, built fast and eager, mostly worked, technically, in the sense that they did erupt. Priti's, built slow and deliberate, erupted spectacularly, structurally sound enough to survive three separate eruptions for three separate class periods, while most of the rush jobs had already crumbled after their first.</p><p>She won first place, somewhat to her own surprise, and told the local paper's brief write-up, when asked her secret, something that made several parents in the audience laugh knowingly: \"I just read the instructions. That's it. That's the whole secret.\" She kept that habit for the rest of her school career, unglamorous as it was, and it kept quietly, consistently, paying off.</p>",
